description.plain:
Karla Camila Cabello Estrabao is a Cuban-American singer born on March 3, 1997, in Cojímar, La Habana, Cuba. For the first five years of her life, Cabello lived in Cuba and Mexico before relocating to Miami, Florida. Cabello dropped out of her 2012/13 high school year to pursue a career in singing (although she did receive her diploma). For her quinceanera, Camila asked her parents to drive her to North Carolina, so she could audition for the second season of The X Factor US. Barely making it into the competition, she was granted an “alternate” role who was only able to audition if they had time. Eventually, she along with Dinah Jane Hansen, Ally Brooke Hernandez, Lauren Jauregui and Normani Kordei were tapped to form multi-platinum girl group, Fifth Harmony. The collective  released many chart-toppers with the highest being “Work From Home” peaking at number 4 on the Billboard Hot 100.

During this time, Cabello collaborated with Canadian artist Shawn Mendes on “I Know What You Did Last Summer,” as well as American rapper Machine Gun Kelly on “Bad Things,” which peaked at number 4 on the Billboard Hot 100.

She remained part of the group until the 19th of December 2016, where the four remaining members announced via their official Twitter account that Camila had decided to leave the group to pursue a solo career. Camila then confirmed this by posting a statement on her Twitter account.

After the split, Camila released pop and dance-influenced debut single, “Crying in The Club” on May 19, 2017 and promotional single, “I Have Questions” two days later. The first 6 months of being a solo also allowed for features to occur: with Cashmere Cat’s “Love Incredible,” J Balvin and Pitbull’s “Hey Ma,” and Major Lazer’s “Know No Better” along with American rappers Travis Scott and Quavo.

On July 20th, 2017 Cabello supported the North American leg of Bruno Mars’s “24K Magic World Tour.” Shortly after on August 4th, she released her “summer double features” “OMG” featuring Quavo, and her solo breakout hit, “Havana” featuring Young Thug. “Havana” was confirmed as a single from her self-titled debut album on August 30th, 2017 via Twitter. The song became a commercial and major success becoming her first #1 hit. The track was certified 5x platinum along with diamond certifications in Brazil and France—making Camila the fastest female artist born in the 90s to achieve a diamond certification, doing so in only 5 months.

On December 4th, 2017, Camila had revealed she changed the title of her debut album from The Hurting, The Healing, The Loving. to Camila. Alongside that announcement, two singles from her album were released; “Real Friends” and “Never Be the Same” on December 7th. The following week “Crown,” a collaboration with Grey for Netflix’s Bright was dropped.

January 12, 2018, marked the release of her solo debut project. Camila debuted at #1 in 100 different countries on iTunes, breaking the record for most #1’s for a debut album. Camila also reached a major milestone on January 21, debuting at #1 on the Billboard 200 Albums chart. Later on April 12, 2018, the album was certified platinum.

2018 saw a few more collaborations for Cabello, starting with the remix of her own hit “Never Be The Same” featuring country singer Kane Brown. “Sangria Wine” with Pharrell, who had worked on “Havana” with Cabello followed, released May 18th. The final three tracks from Cabello in 2018 were all remixes. Bazzi’s “Beautiful;” Cabello’s “Real Friends” featuring Swae Lee and an orchestral version of “Consequences” from Camila.

In January of  2019, shortly after her debut’s anniversary, Camila revealed that she began writing for her second album. On June 3, 2019, she posted an Instagram story of a Dropbox folder named CC2, suggesting she had completed the album.

A few days prior to this, Camila was featured on Mark Ronson’s track “Find U Again.” Later that month, Camila combined forces with Shawn Mendes once again to create “Señorita” which was accompanied by a steamy music video.

Camila’s second album was announced in conjunction with the released of two singles, “Shameless” and “Liar.” Within the next five weeks, Camila released two more singles, “Cry for Me” and “Easy”, which she performed live during her Saturday Night Live debut on October 12, 2019.

On November 13, 2019, Camila revealed the release date and album art for Romance, announcing that another single, “Living Proof” would be released later that week.

songs.title: Havana

description.plain:
“Havana” is about Camila falling in love “with this bad boy from Havana.” It is also an ode to her hometown. Camila was born in Cojímar, award – or consejo popular – that belongs to the municipality of La Habana Del Este, which is a district of Havana.  Camila immigrated to the US when she was still a kid:

 I was almost 7 at the time, born in Havana, Cuba. My papá is puro Mexicano and we lived back and forth between the heat of Havana and the concrete jungle of Mexico City. I didn’t realize it then, but, boy, does it hit me now. I realize how scary it must have been for them.

The song was released as a “Summer Double Feature” along with “OMG” from Camila Cabello’s debut album. The song’s music video was released on October 24. On November 9, a “vertical video” was released for the track.

Camila confirmed it to be a single on August 30. As “Crying in the Club” won’t be included on the album, “Havana” is the lead single of the record. Camila has publicly stated that some people doubted that “Havana” had the potential of being a single, including herself. As of now, it is her favorite song to perform.

There are at least nine versions of the song, including a solo version, a Spanglish version, and a Spanglish remix featuring Daddy Yankee. In an interview with 98.7 AMP, Camila stated that Havana was the hardest song to write of the whole album:

I have performed a version of it in Chicago for a radio show that I had. And, before the song came out, I re-wrote the pre-chorus. That’s how many different times the song had to be worked on.

According to producer Louis Bell, “Havana” is definitely a “Camila song” and it changed the tone of her debut album:

The album started off more serious — dealing with relationship stuff, dealing with a lot of heartbreak, dealing with a lot of life things, with the Fifth Harmony thing. It started off darker, but then towards the end, it lightened up because of where she was in her life. She felt more liberated.

The track eventually reached #1 on the Billboard Hot 100, becoming Thug’s first #1 hit and Cabello’s first solo #1 hit as a lead artist. On April 12, 2018, the song was certified 5x multi-platinum.

On July 3rd, 2018, “Havana” ended it’s 46 week run on the Billboard Hot 100, making it her first solo single to spend the most weeks on the Hot 100.

songs.lyrics:
[Intro: Pharrell Williams]
Hey

[Chorus: Camila Cabello & Pharrell Williams]
Havana, ooh, na-na (Hey)
Half of my heart is in Havana, ooh na-na (Hey, hey)
He took me back to East Atlanta, na-na-na, ah
Oh, but my heart is in Havana (Hey)
There's somethin' 'bout his manners (Uh-huh)

songs.full_title: Never Be The Same by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Never Be The Same

description.plain:
According to a 2018 HITS Daily Double interview, “Never Be the Same” was initially titled “Nicotine.” Its December 7 drop date was announced via Twitter on December 6, 2017. The single was released alongside “Real Friends.”

Camila Cabello teased an unofficial music video via Twitter on December 29, 2017, calling it a “New Year’s Eve gift” for her fans. On February 14, 2018, she announced her first tour as a solo artist, which was named after the song. According to a 2017 Rolling Stone article, it was “inspired by a relationship she had a couple of years back.”

Camila also considers it to be the best track she’s written so far, explaining in a September 2017 Official Charts article that it only took an hour to write. “Never Be The Same” can be seen as the prequel of the relationship that broke Camila in her subsequent January 2018 track, “Consequences”:

…It’s kind of like the aftermath of ‘Never Be the Same.’ I feel like a lot of the songs could be in this one story, and all the different phases, and I feel like ‘Consequences’ is the aftermath of a love that was intoxicating like that, and hard to get out of your mind; or the kind of love that you compare to everybody else and it’s not the same.

–from Coup de Main magazine (February 2018)

songs.full_title: Crying In The Club by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Crying In The Club

description.plain:
“Crying in the Club” is the Cuban songstress Camila Cabello’s first solo single. The song is a fiery anthem about uplifting yourself after a downfall. The track was initially supposed to be on her debut album, Camila, (previously The Hurting, The Healing, The Loving) but she later revealed that it had been dropped from the final tracklist.

To promote the song, Camila sent fans part of the cover art in order to complete and reveal the artwork. She gave her first live performance of the track at the 2017 Billboard Music Awards, where she also sang “I Have Questions” as a part of Xfinity Encore at the show.

Camila broke down the song ON AIR with Ryan Seacrest, saying:

For me, the club is kind of like a euphemism. The lyrics say stuff like “Let the music lift you up like you’ve never been this free, let the music lift you up like you’ve never been so high.” I feel like for me, that was more of what the writing process and what the album making process was saying to me.

In a 2019 interview to The Telegraph, Camila confessed that she regrets releasing “Crying in the Club”:

I didn’t write and it didn’t feel like me. I had the chorus to “Havana”, but I went with what was safe, what industry people said had worked before. Turns out, no one has a clue.

songs.full_title: Shameless by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Shameless

description.plain:
Camila Cabello started off her sophomore album, Romance with a bang, giving listeners not one, but two tracks that see her finally facing her feelings about a crush. In conjunction with the release of “Shameless,” a music video for the song was released, directed by Henry Scholfield, who has previously worked with Billie Eilish and Dua Lipa.

The track was first hinted at on August 12, 2019, when  Camila was spotted filming a music video in Los Angeles. During this shoot, the unreleased track was heard, with a  “Celebrity Photo Agency” called BACKGRID TV posting a video of the shoot to YouTube, which included part of the track’s audio.

As part of Spotify’s “The Romance Experience,” Camila commented on the track:

I love songs that talk about making love and the connection. And how amazing and almost transcendent it feels when you have you have that find of intimacy with somebody that you’re in love with.

songs.full_title: Real Friends by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Real Friends

description.plain:
“Real Friends” is an introspective track from Camila Cabello in which she struggles to find genuine friends:

This song is about feeling lonely and disilluded by people in LA while I was away from home

https://twitter.com/Camila_Cabello/status/938880060538400768

On December 6, a day before the release of “Real Friends,” Camila tweeted that the single’s cover art has drawings by her younger sister, Sofia Cabello. Three days later, she revealed that “Real Friends” almost didn’t make it to the album because the song had been finished too close to the deadline. It’s one of the songs she’s had the most fun writing for the album.

“Real Friends” can be seen as a follow-up to her promotional single “I Have Questions”, where she confronts her supposed friends, as this track is Camila’s search for new friendships after leaving her unhealthy friends behind. It’s also one of the two tracks which Camila feels that best represent her in the album.

Camila first performed this song on Lollapalooza Argentina 2018.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j9xNGKR2o3E

songs.full_title: My Oh My by Camila Cabello (Ft. DaBaby)
songs.title: My Oh My

description.plain:
“My Oh My” sees Camila go against her parents' judgment and pursue a “bad boy,” in a situation similar to her August 2017 single “Havana.” The track is the only feature sophomore album, Romance, and marks the first time Camila and DaBaby have worked together.

The song was announced in a review by The Sun, published November 27, 2019, who dubbed the track as the sequel to “Havana.”

Initially, the track did not appear on CD versions of Romance, including the Target Exclusive Version. Coincidentally, “My Oh My” was the only track from Romance (aside from the earlier singles) that was not leaked during a drop two weeks prior to release.

songs.full_title: Consequences by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Consequences

description.plain:
“Consequences” can be seen as the follow-up of the relationship portrayed in “Never Be The Same”:

It’s kind of like the aftermath of “Never Be the Same”. I feel like a lot of the songs could be in this one story, and all the different phases, and I feel like “Consequences” is the aftermath of a love that was intoxicating like that and hard to get out of your mind or the kind of the love that you compare to everybody else and it’s not the same.

The track is one of the first songs from the album that Camila worked on, hinted at a year before the song’s release via Twitter. In a livestream, Camila mentioned “Consequences” was one of the songs from her album that she was most excited to share with her fans.

Several months later, Camila released the track as a single, which featured an orchestra. It would mark her final release for the album, leading to a well-deserved break before beginning work on her second album.

songs.full_title: I Have Questions by Camila Cabello
songs.title: I Have Questions

description.plain:
“I Have Questions” is a single by Camila Cabello, intended to be on her debut self-titled album but was scrapped when the theme was altered. The track was born in late 2015/early 2016, whilst still touring with Fifth Harmony, and wasn’t lyrically finished until a year later.
“I Have Questions” can be seen as the precedent to Camila’s life after the release of “Real Friends” where Camila’s search for new friendships after leaving her unhealthy friends behind, while in this track she confronts her supposed friends for the harm they’ve done to her.

She teased the song with this tweet:
https://twitter.com/Camila_Cabello/status/835039955009208320

The track was released a promotional single on May 22, 2017, along with a lyric video. The beginning of the song is also featured on the music video of “Crying in the Club”.

She has stated that “I Have Questions” is about friendship, not a romantic relationship:

I had a friend and we were so close and, literally like a day after, we didn’t even know each other.

In an interview to Flaunt, Camila said she believed that the end of a friendship hurts more than a romantic break-up:

In a romantic relationship you think, this is amazing, this is beautiful, I love this person, but there’s a part of you that’s always prepared for it to end. I feel with a friendship you think it’s going to last forever. You start to consider that person like your family and so you don’t see an end to that. So when it’s like a shocking or abrupt ending that’s worse.

https://twitter.com/Camila_Cabello/status/1036369113231314949

songs.full_title: Liar by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Liar

description.plain:
“Liar” is a song by singer-songwriter Camila Cabello released alongside “Shameless”. This release was dubbed as “Installment One” of her sophomore album, Romance. A music video for the song was released on September 12. This isn’t the first time Camila has given fans two tracks concurrently, with chart-topper “Havana” accompanying “OMG” as 2017 “Summer Double Features.”

The jazz-tinged song – which samples Ace Of Base’s 90s hit “All That She Wants”“ and Lionel Richie’s 1983 song “All Night Long (All Night)”–finds Camila losing control as she falls in love, despite denying her feelings.

Camila summarised the track in Spotify’s “The Romance Experience”:

It’s like the person you don’t wanna like. ‘Cause you know that he would just mess me up, and my stomach would be in knots. It just got to the point where it was funny because every time I’d be like, 'I don’t like him’ […] I knew I was just lying to myself.

songs.full_title: I LUV IT by Camila Cabello & Playboi Carti
songs.title: I LUV IT

description.plain:
“I LUV IT” serves as the lead single for her album C,XOXO.

 The track’s title was teased in a series of Instagram posts throughout February 2024, before Camila posted the first snippet of the song to her Instagram on March 5, 2024. On the same day during an NBA game between the Miami Heat and the Detroit Pistons, Camila was spotted sporting a basketball jersey reading “I LUV IT”, handing a copy to Jimmy Butler before the game.

A demo version of the track leaked on March 21, 2024, before the official release date and pre-save link was announced by Camila on her socials on March 25, 2024. The song and its accompanied video were released on all streaming platforms on March 27, 2024.

The track samples the chorus from Gucci Mane’s 2009 song “Lemonade” and interpolates Rihanna’s 2011 hit track “Cockiness (Love It)”.

songs.full_title: Bam Bam by Camila Cabello (Ft. Ed Sheeran)
songs.title: Bam Bam

description.plain:
Coming months after her breakup with Shawn Mendes, “Bam Bam” is Camila Cabello’s anthem about moving on and accepting inevitability in losing a partner. Things change, and one can’t dwell on that for too long.

The track was inspired by a saying of her mother, “Así e' la vida” (English: “That’s how life is”). This saying is referenced in the chorus.

Featuring “South of the Border” collaborator Ed Sheeran, “Bam Bam” is the second promotional single for Camila Cabello’s third studio album, Familia.

Beginning February 21, 2022 when she first announced the song, Cabello teased multiple parts on TikTok.

songs.full_title: Living Proof by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Living Proof

description.plain:
On November 13, 2019, Camila revealed the album art and release date for her sophomore album Romance, whilst announcing that “Living Proof” would be released later that week, as the album’s fifth (solo) single. In the announcement post, Camila commented:

(It is) one of the first and one of my favorite songs I wrote for the album.

The track was first hinted to when Camila  tweeted about it in February 2019, telling fans:

I showed my fam the songs I have so far last night, a unanimous favorite is a song called “Living Proof.”

Unbeknownst to fans at the time, on June 29, 2019, Camila shared a snippet of the track online, featuring part of the second verse.

The song has been performed live for the first time at the AMAs on November 24, 2019, alongside the release of the music video.

songs.full_title: Something's Gotta Give by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Something’s Gotta Give

description.plain:
“Something’s Gotta Give, originally titled "A Good Reason To Go,” is a tear-jerker of a track, based on a relationship Camila had.

In a livestream, Camila revealed that “Something’s Gotta Give” is one of the songs that she was most nervous to share with her fans because “it’s really personal”.  In a tweet, Camila confessed that she once sang “Something’s Gotta Give” and had to take a break because she broke down crying.

Camila revealed that this is her parents' favorite track on Camila. It was first performed live on the Never Be The Same Tour at Vancouver. There, Camila implied that “Something’s Gotta Give” might have a political or social meaning as well.

songs.full_title: Easy by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Easy

description.plain:
“Easy” is the fourth song released from Camila’s sophomore studio album, Romance following “Shameless,” “Liar” and “Cry for Me,” released only a week earlier.

Fans first heard the song in June 2019, when Camila posted a video of herself lip-syncing to the pre-chorus on Instagram and Twitter.

In the track, Camila addresses her significant other, detailing the ways in which they helped her love herself, and feel loved for the first time. When talking to Elle in September 2019, Camila revealed that she had not experienced falling in love with someone up until the year prior, saying:

I think there is so much more depth to love when you know you are in it with another person.

songs.full_title: She Loves Control by Camila Cabello
songs.title: She Loves Control

description.plain:
“She Loves Control” is a sassy track about a bossy girl who wants things her way. Camila herself has admitted that she is, in fact, a control freak, stating that the track was inspired by her wanting “creative control.”

I basically wrote it about this time in my life where I just loved having control. Control creatively, control of my life, my decisions, control of my time. I wrote it knowing it could be about whatever you wanted it to be, but for me that’s where it stemmed from.

Whilst producer Louis Bell saw the track possible summertime single, this never became a reality:

I think, timing-wise, the way “Never Be the Same” is going now, and leading into the summer, that would be an ideal single to come up next.

songs.full_title: All These Years by Camila Cabello
songs.title: All These Years

description.plain:
“All These Years” is was first heard by fans on August 4, 2017, when played a snippet of it during a livestream. Camila mention it was one of the tracks she was most nervous to share with her fans because “it’s really personal”. The lyrics are based on a relationship Camila had. She first performed this song on Lollapalooza Argentina 2018.

In a tweet, Camila revealed that she actually wrote “All These Years” to acoustic guitar in fifteen minutes before producer Frank Dukes came in and “did his magic.”

songs.full_title: First Man by Camila Cabello
songs.title: First Man

description.plain:
In “First Man”, Camila sings directly to her father, Alejandro, trying to ease his worry about the relationship she was in. Camila revealed that “First Man” was the first song written for Romance, in Nashville. She added:

I was so happy with it… That was definitely the proudest I’ve ever been with writing a song.

At the time of writing, Camila was dating Matthew Hussey. The pair dated for over a year before splitting up in June 2019.

The track was leaked to SoundCloud on November 8, 2018, over a year prior to its official release, but was later taken down by the original poster. Cabello performed it live at the 2020 Grammy Awards ceremony with her father in the audience.

songs.full_title: In the Dark by Camila Cabello
songs.title: In the Dark

description.plain:
“In The Dark” is the ninth track of Camila Cabello’s  debut album, Camila. It was written the day after the 59th Grammy’s, held in February 2017, when the Cabello was presenting one of the nominees, about an “encounter with an unnamed famous boy”. The Sun’s review of the album described the track as a smooth R&B tune. Camila considers it as one of the two songs in the album which give the fans the best idea about who she really is.

She has teased the song on her social media accounts twice: on July, 2017 and on December, 2017.

songs.full_title: Don't Go Yet by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Don’t Go Yet

description.plain:
Cabello’s first release since her second studio album, Romance in late 2019, “Don’t Go Yet” marks Cabello’s return to music as the first single from her third studio album, Familia. Indulging her Latin roots, the song features Camila asking her lover to stay with her for the night. The lover in question is likely Cabello’s boyfriend at the time of release, Canadian superstar Shawn Mendes.

Notably, the song features songwriting from Scott Harris, who has been a frequent collaborator and writer on some of Shawn Mendes’ biggest hits.

songs.full_title: Should've Said It by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Should’ve Said It

description.plain:
In “Should’ve Said It,” Camila calls out a former love interest on their poor timing, as she is now in a relationship with someone else. The track appears to be a dig at Shawn Mendes, whom she began dating after breaking up with 2018-2019 boyfriend Matthew Hussey. Despite this, the track is his favorite from the album.

The song title was initially found hidden on a poster that came with a Target Exclusive CD version of Romance. In November 2019, the track was first displayed publicly on Camila’s BMI Repertoire.

songs.full_title: Cry for Me by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Cry for Me

description.plain:
“Cry for Me” is the third single released from Camila’s sophomore studio album, Romance following the release of “Liar” and “Shameless”. Backed by upbeat production, the song finds Camila dealing from a breakup, wanting her ex-lover to feel as melancholic as she herself is feeling.

Following the song’s release, Camila took to Instagram, telling fans that although the song was only written a few months prior, it was inspired by one of her early works:

i wrote a song back when I was 16 called I’m pissed off you’re happy, about a situation where someone and I broke up and sooner than I expected, they moved on, they were having fun and happy and dating and i was just like…. what the hell, that didn’t take very long 🤬🤬🤬🤬 I took that idea and put it into this song, the feeling nobody likes to admit about feeling wild with jealousy. [sic]

songs.full_title: Used to This by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Used to This

description.plain:
During a Facebook live stream held in London on October 1, 2019, Camila recited a snippet of an unreleased track, titled “Used To This.” She also revealed that the song was “the one (she) did with FINNEAS” – a collaboration she had previously mentioned to Zane Lowe on September 9, 2019.

On October 24, 2019, Camila took to Instagram to hold a brief Q&A session. During this session, one fan asked, what song Camila was most excited for people to hear. In reply, Camila played a 5-second snippet of an unreleased track, posting it to her Instagram story. Along with the audio, the video featured text, which said, “think I need a drink.”

These lyrics were later revealed to be part of “Used To This” when People reported on Camila’s intimate LA session in November 2019. During the session, she revealed that the song was the last to be written for Romance.

songs.full_title: Bad Kind of Butterflies by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Bad Kind of Butterflies

description.plain:
“Bad Kind of Butterflies” sees Camila confess that despite being in a happy relationship, there’s someone else stuck in her head.

The bass-heavy track appears to narrate the moment when Camila and Matthew Hussey ended their relationship, after dating for over a year.  The break-up was spurred by Camila’s feelings for collaborator Shawn Mendes, with the pair becoming a couple not long after.

At her Los Angeles pop-up on December 6, 2019, Camila confessed that she hasn’t listened to the track since she recorded it:

It takes me back to a time when I was always feeling anxious. Just thinking about writing [the song] makes me want to throw up.

songs.full_title: Feel It Twice by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Feel It Twice

description.plain:
In “Feel It Twice” Camila sympathizes with an old flame who has finally realized he has feelings for her. The topic of realizing feelings too late is also touched on in album-mate “Should’ve Said It.” Both tracks are about the same person, penned during the first week of the Romance sessions.

Camila explained the song’s content:

This person had been my friend and we were really, really close and when he confessed that he had feelings for me, things kind of got awkward because we weren’t together. I felt like I was hurting him and I felt weird because it felt like we were kind of drifting away as friends.

songs.full_title: Into It by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Into It

description.plain:
With “sharp and catchy production,” “Into It” is “the sexiest tune” of Camila Cabello’s debut self-titled album.

This track was first announced during an Instagram livestream on August 4th, 2017. Official Charts considered it to be the “real gem” of the record, while Uproxx picked “Into It” as the 16th best pop song in 2018 so far.

In an interview with Beats1, Camila talked about the song;

The track was something I forever working on. I just tried every single possibility… It [the album] ends with this new chapter, ‘cause once you’re done with all the stuff you’re bummed out about, you have all this room to feel the more fun stuff.

According to producer Louis Bell, the track is all about Camila showing her fun side:

[This song] was a chance for her to be playful and flirty and show that side of her and not feel like there’s any limitations of how her album could sound. We didn’t have anything else that sounded like that.

songs.full_title: Only Told the Moon by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Only Told the Moon

description.plain:
“Only Told  the Moon” leaked on February, 2017. In an interview to 997NOW, Camila revealed that she wrote and produced the song on Garage Band in a hotel room when she was 16. She also mentioned that, although the track is not going to be on her debut album, she wanted it to feature on her next one because “it’s a special enough song”.

It’s important to note that Camila did not compose the instrumental part of this song. When she began writing songs, Camila would use instrumental songs that already existed.

The moon is an important symbol to Camila:

I’ve just always loved the moon and thought it was really, really beautiful. I’ve always loved to personify it as a friend because I remember being a kid and driving in the car and you always see it. I don’t know why I personify the moon as a “her”, but I do. Even in songs that I write, I personify the moon and the sun a lot. I don’t know why, but I do.

https://twitter.com/Camila_Cabello/status/992184854891651072

songs.full_title: Scar Tissue by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Scar Tissue

description.plain:
“Scar Tissue” is a in development track which was believed to be on her upcoming album Camila. A low quality of the song was leaked on August 31, 2017, then a higher quality version surfaced online on January 5, 2018.

Singer Charli XCX is credited in the writing of the song along with Camila. The duo has also worked together in “OMG” and “Señorita”.

A release of the album’s tracklist revealed the “Scar Tissue” will not be on the album. Talking to Zach Sang on the future of “Scar Tissue,” Camila said she hoped to “develop it more for the next album or something else”. In a livestream celebrating the release of Camila, she stated that “Scar Tissue” was not included in the record because “it was not ready for the album”.

Camila first performed the song live on April 9, 2018, the first stop on her Never Be the Same Tour with “Sangria Wine” which was also unreleased at the time.

description.plain:
“Crown” is a song from the soundtrack of Bright, a Netflix thriller starring Will Smith, Joel Edgerton, and Noomi Rapace. The movie was released worldwide on December 22, 2017.

The song is the first collaboration from EDM producer’s Grey who came into light with “Starving” and “Havana” crooner Camila Cabello.

Both Camila Cabello & Grey teased “Crown” on their Twitter:

https://twitter.com/Camila_Cabello/status/928301326123044866
https://twitter.com/greymusic/status/928275946875920386

And the week before the soundtracks premiere, Camila shared a snippet of the song:

https://twitter.com/Camila_Cabello/status/940665058312491008

songs.full_title: HE KNOWS by Camila Cabello & Lil Nas X
songs.title: HE KNOWS

description.plain:
“HE KNOWS” is a single by artist Camila Cabello featuring Lil Nas X. It samples Ojerime’s “Give it Up 2 Me”, and was released on streaming platforms on Friday, May 10, 2024. It is a playful, energetic track, and is featured on Cabello’s album, “C,XOXO” as the fourth track. The album was released on June 28, 2024.

A music video was uploaded to Youtube on the 22nd of May.

This song marks Cabello’s second single of 2024 (With the first being “I LUV IT ft. Playboi Carti”) and Lil Nas X’s third feature in his career.

Camila Cabello first announced the collaboration on her Instagram with the captions: “SHE’S A PROVOCATEUR, DANCEFLOOR CONNOISSEUR” on May 8, and Lil Nas X announced the single on his Instagram on the same date.

songs.full_title: HOT UPTOWN by Camila Cabello (Ft. Drake)
songs.title: HOT UPTOWN

description.plain:
“HOT UPTOWN” is the eighth track on Camila Cabello’s fourth album, C,XOXO. The song features Drake exploring themes of love, desire, and reconciliation amidst luxury and materialism. Drake opens with references to luxury items like Nike shoes and Benz cars, hinting at a glamorous lifestyle. Camila Cabello joins in with emotive vocals in the refrain and chorus, expressing longing and a desire to rekindle love, particularly when things get heated uptown. The post-chorus emphasizes physical intimacy, highlighting a passionate connection. Throughout the verses, Drake reflects on the challenges and efforts involved in maintaining a relationship, while Camila asserts her self-worth and the value of her love. The song blends Drake’s rap verses with Camila’s melodic vocals, creating a narrative of love, attraction, and the pursuit of happiness amidst life’s luxuries.
This song contains many references to the other Drake feature on this album in the song “Uuugly”. The song “Uuugly” is also about a breakup where the main speaker is Drake, in contrast to this song where the main speaker is Camilia. This can be seen as two different perspectives over the same breakup.

songs.full_title: Hasta Los Dientes by Camila Cabello (Ft. Maria Becerra)
songs.title: Hasta Los Dientes

description.plain:
Luego de adelantarlo por meses, la cantante cubana-mexicana-estadounidense Camila Cabello, y la cantante argentina, María Becerra, nos traen su colaboración “Hasta Los Dientes”, una canción pop con influencias disco en donde describen sus sentimientos sobre sus parejas actuales, a quienes celan por haber tenido un pasado con otra mujer.

En septiembre de 2021, mientras estaba en un vivo de TikTok, Camila dió a conocer que María participaría de su tercer álbum de estudio, Familia.
Por los próximos cinco meses, las dos artistas confirmaron que el lanzamiento de la canción era inminente, y que hasta se grabó un videoclip para tal.

El 30 de marzo de 2022, Camila subió un adelanto de la canción en TikTok y el 8 de abril lanzó el álbum, Familia. El 13 de mayo Camila lanzó el videoclip de la canción.

songs.full_title: La Buena Vida by Camila Cabello
songs.title: La Buena Vida

description.plain:
During her NPR Tiny Desk (Home) Concert posted online on October 15, 2021, Camila Cabello closed with an unreleased song titled “La Buena Vida.” The performance gave fans another taste of Camila’s third studio album, Familia, following on from the release of “Don’t Go Yet.”

The track’s Spanish title translates to “the good life” in English.

Whilst introducing the track, Camila revealed that it was one of her favorite songs from the album. When promoting the performance on Twitter, she also revealed that her father, Alejandro, features on the studio version.

songs.title: ​everyone at this party

description.plain:
“everyone at this party” is the closing track to Camila Cabello’s third studio album, Familia. In the acoustic ballad, Camila reflects on a past relationship in which the person she was dating, most likely Shawn Mendes since it’s her most recent relationship, needed a break, but she still has feelings for him.

She teased the song for the first time on March 29, 2022, on her TikTok account.

songs.full_title: Boys Don't Cry by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Boys Don’t Cry

description.plain:
On “Boys Don’t Cry,” Camila reflects on how toxic masculinity affects her partner and the consequences it has in their relationship. The midtempo song is the most R&B leaning track Camila has released to date and it also features a fluegelhorn played throughout the song.

The lyrics of the track are most likely directed at Camila’s relationship with fellow musician Shawn Mendes, who has opened up about the way toxic masculinity affects him in an interview with ET Canada.

She teased the song for the first time on her TikTok on March 27, 2022.

songs.full_title: Lola by Camila Cabello (Ft. Yotuel)
songs.title: Lola

description.plain:
“Lola” is the 11th track on Camila Cabello’s 3rd studio album, Familia. Enrique Santos previously gave an exclusive interview with Camila Cabello. In this interview Camila revealed the existence of the song, which is a collaboration with Cuban singer Yotuel.

“Yo había hecho una canción con Yotuel, en mi nuevo disco, que se llama Lola.” (I had made a song with Yotuel, on my new album, which is called Lola.)

songs.full_title: Quiet by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Quiet

description.plain:
On “Quiet,” Camila opens up about the way she feels and how her body reacts when she’s close to the boy she likes. She’s most likely talking about Shawn Mendes, since most tracks from Familia were written before the couple split on November, 2021.

On the day the album dropped, Ricky Reed, producer of the track, mentioned on Twitter how it was a last minute addition to the album.

“Quiet” was a crazy last min addition. It was one of the first songs started by Scott and Camila, but never finished. So when we did our final album listen-back, Camila mentioned “Quiet” and we were like “fuck it, let’s try to write a second verse. And it came out CRAZY!!!

The song was teased by the Havana singer on April 6th, 2022 via her TikTok account.

“Quiet” was a crazy last min addition. It was one of the first songs started by Scott and Camila, but never finished. So when we did our final album listen-back, Camila mentioned “Quiet” and we were like “fuck it, let’s try to write a second verse. And it came out CRAZY!!!

The song was teased by the Havana singer on April 6th, 2022 via her TikTok account.

songs.title: Cinderella

description.plain:
“Cinderella” is a song written and produced by Camila Cabello that was leaked in February, 2017. It is a feminist outtake of the popular tale of Cinderella.

It’s important to note that Camila did not compose the instrumental part of this song. When she first began writing songs, Camila would use instrumental songs that already existed.

songs.full_title: Must Be Love by Camila Cabello
songs.title: Must Be Love

description.plain:
“Must Be Love” is an unreleased song by Cuban-Mexican singer, Camila Cabello. Throughout this song, Camila sings about a breakup, and how much it has affected her. She thought the relationship was true love which is why she feels devastated.

It is speculated to be an outtake from her debut album, Camila. The song was teased on a livestream on July 7. It was teased again by Music Mafia on February 28, 2018 and was teased once more on March 22, 2018. The full track leaked to the public via SoundCloud on April 11, 2018. It is currently unknown if the song will be released officially.

annotatable.title: Must Be Love

body.plain:
“Must Be Love” is an unreleased song by Cuban-Mexican singer, Camila Cabello. Throughout this song, Camila sings about a breakup, and how much it has affected her. She thought the relationship was true love which is why she feels devastated.

It is speculated to be an outtake from her debut album, Camila. The song was teased on a livestream on July 7. It was teased again by Music Mafia on February 28, 2018 and was teased once more on March 22, 2018. The full track leaked to the public via SoundCloud on April 11, 2018. It is currently unknown if the song will be released officially.
